review_blob: Dark reddish-brown with a moderate light brown head. Aroma of licorice, alcohol. Flavor is sweet, roasty, licorice, with a bitter finish. Full, foamy mouthfeel. On the lighter end of the imperial stout scale, but nicely balanced and quite drinkable.
Clear golden-yellow with no head. Faint sweet/spicy/yeasty aroma. Full body, almost flat. Caramel sweet with a bitter/sweet finish.
Hazy amber/gold with a good off-white head. Aroma is hops. Medium body, foamy mouthfeel. Briefy and faintly malty, then strongly hoppy with a very bitter finish and lingering bitter aftertaste.
Dark ruby brown with a scant off-white head. Aroma of licorice and hops. Creamy mouthfeel, full body. Licorice, roasty and bitter with a little malty sweetness for balance. An exemplary porter.
Copper/amber with an offwhite head. Strong grapefruit aroma. Strong hop flavor, well balanced. Low bitterness for an IPA. Awesome blast of hoppy freshness in a very drinkable beer.
Pale yellow, clear until bottom on the bottle. Moderate white head. Fruity/yeasty aroma. Light body, foamy mouthfeel. Flavor is wheat malt, yeast, delicate hops, slightly sour.
Dark brown with a modest, light brown head. Aroma is roasty and cocoa. Medium body, slippery mouthfeel. Roasty, hoppy. No hint of chocolate/cocoa.
Light brown with a modest off-white head. Sour and alcoholic aroma. Full-bodied with a foamy mouthfeel. Sweet then sour then bitter. A little spicy.
Dark brown with a small, quick tan head. Roasty/malty/alcoholic aroma. Medium body, smooth, foamy mouthfeel. Dry, roasty, and hoppy. Some coffee and caramel/malt. Good, solid porter.

Cloudy amber with a small, off-white head. Intense fruity/hoppy bouquet. Full body, foamy mouthfeel. Sweet/malty at first, then hoppy/bitter, with a bitter finish. Great fresh, hoppy flavor. A very good IPA.
Brown with a thin, tan head. Caramely, spicy, alcoholic aroma. Malty, hoppy, spicy. Creamy mouthfeel. Bitter finish. Good balance. Unique and enjoyable.

Very dark reddish-brown with a small light brown head. Aroma is licorice/anise and molasses. Wow. Explosion of intense flavors: hops, roasty malt, molasses, alcohol. Very full-bodied with a thick mouthfeel. All dials set to 11.
Reddish-brown with no head. Roasty/malty aroma. Full-bodied. Malty at first, hoppy finish. Bitter aftertaste. Quite hoppy. Not bad, but I obviously got an undercarbonated bottle.
Very dark with a full, dark tan head. Aroma is malty, roasty, licorice, alcohol. Full body. Sweet but with ample hops for balance. Coffee/roasty flavor. Delicious and rich with a nice hops kick.
beer_name: North Coast Old Rasputin Russian Imperial Stout

review_blob: Not bad for what it is. The spices are fairly low-keyed, but theyre definitely there. Pours a pretty, clear amber with a tan head. Aroma is malty and spicy, as expected.

To me this is more like an imperial stout than a strong ale. Its intense in pretty much every way a beer can be: color, aroma, taste, mouthfeel, and alcohol. The only thing its not intense in is hops--not that its underhopped. The aroma is alcohol and fruit. Mouthfeel is thick and velvety. Flavor is sweet, woody, roasty with subtle bitterness and a sour finish. Intense and satisfying.

Dark brown with a decent, tan head. Aroma is spicy, licorice, and alcoholic. Medium-bodied with a creamy/foamy mouthfeel. Malty, sweet, roasty, and spicy. Hops are in the background, more obvious at the finish. Very tasty and complex.

Hazy amber/gold with a small offwhite head. Aroma is hops with a hint of malt. Full bodied with a creamy/foamy mouthfeel. Sharply bitter, but still some underlying sweetness for balance. Classic west-coast American IPA. Very nice.
Hazy copper with a modest offwhite head. Aroma is malt and alcohol. Medium body. Sharply balanced--strong malt and strong hops. A quality beer, but fairly basic.
Dark reddish brown with an abundant, persistent tan head. Licorice aroma. Full mouthfeel, little carbonation. Malty sweet, roasty, with a spicy and hoppy finish. Complex and unusual...enjoyable.

beer_brewer_name: Yakima Brewing And Malting Co./Bert Grants Real Ales
review_blob: Orangish amber with an offwhite head. Malty/alcohol aroma. Medium-bodied with a lightly foamy mouthfeel. Lots of malt with low-level hops for balance. Slightly sweet, lingering hoppy aftertaste. Pleasant and delicious. Very quaffable.

Slightly hazy yellow with a rapidly disappearing head. Fruity-yeasty aroma. Fizzy mouthfeel, medium body. Tangy and hoppy, but not bitter. Some fruity yeast flavor.
Surprisingly substantial for an American blonde. Nice, different.

Clear gold with a full, persistent, nearly white head. Fresh hoppy aroma. Medium-bodied. Malty-sweet at first, but quickly progresses to hops and more hops, with a lingering hoppy aftertaste. Slightly too clean for an ale, a little under-hopped for an American IPA. Delicious, but I wouldnt have pegged it for an IPA.

Copper/amber with a modest off-white head. Very little aroma, mostly hops and malt.
Medium body. Hoppy at the start, malty finish. Good balance. Very drinkable, but not too exciting.
Bark brown with a nice, tan head. Faint aroma of alcohol and licorice. Medium-bodied, malty/licorice flavor with hoppy undertones and roasty finish. Fairly stong. Unusual but pleasant.

Dark ruby-brown with abundant, lasting light brown head. Aroma is roasty, malty, alcoholic, licorice. Full-bodied, foamy mouthfeel, roasty/hoppy flavor. Tasty, well-balanced, easy-to-drink. A finely-crafted stout.

Very dark ruby-brown with a moderate, light brown head. Stains the glassxi 
  yellow.
  Aroma is hops, malt, smokiness, molasses, and mocha.
  Full-bodied, smooth mouthfeel, hoppy, but well balanced with roasted malt.
  Very flavorful but not so overpowering that it has to be sipped. Gorgeous and
  delicious. More like a light imperial stout
 than a dubbel.

Opaque brown with a very meager medium brown head. Stains glass amber. Molasses, licorice, smoky, alcoholic aroma. Wow... Sweet, alcoholic, molasses, licorice flavor initially. Hoppy finish. Very full body with a slippery/velvety mouthfeel. Very little carbonation. Literally tastes like "beer concentrate", but in a good way. Very intense, unique.
Copper with a tan head. Hoppy aroma. Roasty and hoppy, hoppy finish. Medium body. Decent, but definitely not balanced. Good hop fix.

Dark copper with a small, fleeting, light tan head. Hoppy aroma with malty/alcoholic undertones. Full body, lightly carbonated, slippery mouthfeel. Hoppy, then sweet and malty, then hoppy again in the finish and aftertaste. Powerful, unique, memorable.

Clear golden/copper with modest slighty off-white head. Faint hoppy/sour aroma. Medium body, clean, balanced, hoppy finish. A quality pale ale, not distinctive but not obviously flawed.

The low ratings suprised me until I saw that it was brewed by AB. OK, so its nothing special... And AB should burn in hell for what theyve done to American beer. But this really isnt bad, and it shouldnt be punished for being produced by AB.
beer_name: Green Valley Brewing Stone Mill Pale Ale

review_blob: Coppery brown with an offwhite head. Faint sweet malty/alcoholic/yeasty aroma. Medium body, creamy texture, malty attack, hoppy finish. Superb quality, very pleasant to drink.
Dark ruby/brown with a tan, shortlived head. Roasty, licorice aroma. Foamy mouthfeel, excellent balance, roasty and hoppy. Excellent, very drinkable. A little light for a stout.

Golden brown with a modest, offwhite head. Hoppy aroma. Wow, no balance here... Hops all the way. Opens with hops flavor, finishes with hops bitterness. Lingering bitter aftertaste. There is some underlying malty sweetness. Full bodied. Excellent. Top-notch American IPA. Hoppy but not too hoppy.

2006, bottle. Dark brown and ruby with a thick light brown head. Hoppy/spicey/alcoholic aroma. Full bodied, foamy mouthfeel. Hoppy but plenty of malt flavor, roasty/hoppy finish. Superb. Rich, festive, artfully crafted.
beer_name: Anchor Our Special Ale (2005 and later)

review_blob: Reddish brown with a thick, persistent tan head. Alcoholic, malty aroma. Full bodied, roasty, hoppy attack but malty finish, good balance. Rich, satisfying, finely crafted.
Delicious apricot aroma. A deceint weizen with a fairly subtle apricot flavor, otherwise. A refreshing, pleasant, understated fruit beer.
UPDATED: JAN 26, 2009

beer_brewer_name: Portland Brewing Company (Pyramid - North American Breweries)
review_blob: Very dark reddish-brown with a medium brown head. Tangy, hoppy aroma. Full mouthfeel, balanced, lightly roasty flavor. Very drinkable.
